<Feature
  title="GPU RENDERING"
  subtitle="wgpu (Vulkan / DX12 / Metal), staged Extract → Prepare → Render, per-row damage tracking."
>
  <h2>Backend</h2>
  <p>Rendering goes through wgpu — Vulkan and DX12 on Windows, Vulkan on Linux, Metal on macOS. Cells, glyphs, image-protocol textures, UI overlays, and the chrome layer all reach the swapchain through the same instance pipeline.</p>

  <h2>Staged Pipeline</h2>
  <p>Each frame moves through three phases: <strong>Extract</strong> takes a <code>RenderableContent</code> snapshot under the per-pane <code>FairMutex</code> in microseconds and releases the lock; <strong>Prepare</strong> is pure CPU work (layout, palette resolution, instance buffer build) with no GPU calls; <strong>Render</strong> submits the prepared instance buffers. The lock is never held during GPU submission.</p>

  <h2>Damage Tracking</h2>
  <p>Per-row dirty tracking keeps idle work near zero. When output is streaming, only changed rows have their instance ranges rewritten; unchanged rows keep their cached instance data. When nothing is changing the renderer skips presentation entirely and the event loop sleeps via <code>ControlFlow::Wait</code>.</p>

  <h2>Glyph Atlas</h2>
  <p>Glyphs rasterize through swash + skrifa hinting and pack into a guillotine-allocated 2048×2048 atlas (R8Unorm + Rgba8Unorm pages, LRU eviction). ASCII is pre-cached at startup so the first frame renders without atlas fills.</p>

</Feature>
